JOHANNESBURG – President Cyril Ramaphosa on Friday announced former deputy chief justice Dikgang Moseneke has been appointed as the leader of the Mediation Team of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Facilitation in the Kingdom of Lesotho. The group will consist of three deputy ministers, namely the Basic Education Department’s Enver Surty, the International Relations and Cooperation’s Makgabo Regina Mhaule and State Security’s Ellen Molekane. “This decision is in line with the resolution that was taken at the SADC Double Troika Summit that was held on 24 April 2018 in Luanda, Republic of Angola, which decided that President Ramaphosa should continue with the facilitation and recommended that he appoint high level personalities to support him,” the Presidency said in a statement. READ: Sisulu meets Lesotho King in damage-control trip Ramaphosa expressed confidence in Moseneke’s experience and expertise in constitutionalism, saying it will assist immensely. “I take this opportunity to thank Justice Moseneke for availing himself to support us in this important mandate as we continue to assist our brothers and sisters in the Kingdom of Lesotho in their search for a lasting and sustainable solution to their political and security challenges,” Ramaphosa added. eNCA